## 5. Body, Time Path, and World Tube

A body moving through space does not only leave a position.
It leaves a time-path.

Let

\[
X(\tau) = (x(\tau), y(\tau), z(\tau), t(\tau))
\]

be the 4D trajectory of a body through space-time.

If the body has shape \(K\subset\mathbb{R}^3\), then its total trace is not only a line, but a **world tube**

\[
\mathcal{W}
=
\bigcup_{\tau}
\big(B(\tau)\times\{\tau\}\big)
\]

This is important for TERA because logical motion is not point-like.
It is embodied, extended, and leaves structured traces.

---

## 6. Tesseract Mapping

To make 4D trajectories readable, TERA uses normalized mapping into a tesseract-like coordinate frame.

Let

\[
\Phi : \mathcal{M} \to [0,1]^4
\]

be a normalization map from the physical or semantic state space into a 4D hypercube.

Then each event becomes

\[
Q(\tau)=\Phi(X(\tau))
\]

and the full trace becomes a readable 4D structure.

The tesseract is therefore not "mysticism".
It is a normalized visualization frame for directional development through space and time.

